[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] In this chapter, we’ll cover some of the most common types of values you’ll find in JavaScript code, and explain the corresponding ways to describe those types in TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This isn’t an exhaustive list, and future chapters will describe more ways to name and use other types.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Types can also appear in many more *places* than just type annotations.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] As we learn about the types themselves, we’ll also learn about the places where we can refer to these types to form new constructs.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] We’ll start by reviewing the most basic and common types you might encounter when writing JavaScript or TypeScript code.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] These will later form the core building blocks of more complex types.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] JavaScript has three very commonly used primitives: `string`, `number`, and `boolean`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Each has a corresponding type in TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] To specify the type of an array like `[1, 2, 3]`, you can use the syntax `number[]`; this syntax works for any type (e.g.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] `string[]` is an array of strings, and so on).
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You may also see this written as `Array<number>`, which means the same thing.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] We’ll learn more about the syntax `T<U>` when we cover *generics*.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript also has a special type, `any`, that you can use whenever you don’t want a particular value to cause typechecking errors.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The `any` type is useful when you don’t want to write out a long type just to convince TypeScript that a particular line of code is okay.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] When you don’t specify a type, and TypeScript can’t infer it from context, the compiler will typically default to `any`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You usually want to avoid this, though, because `any` isn’t type-checked.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Use the compiler flag `noImplicitAny` to flag any implicit `any` as an error.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] In most cases, though, this isn’t needed.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Wherever possible, TypeScript tries to automatically *infer* the types in your code.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] For the most part you don’t need to explicitly learn the rules of inference.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] If you’re starting out, try using fewer type annotations than you think - you might be surprised how few you need for TypeScript to fully understand what’s going on.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Functions are the primary means of passing data around in JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript allows you to specify the types of both the input and output values of functions.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] When you declare a function, you can add type annotations after each parameter to declare what types of parameters the function accepts.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can also add return type annotations.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Much like variable type annotations, you usually don’t need a return type annotation because TypeScript will infer the function’s return type based on its `return` statements.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The type annotation in the above example doesn’t change anything.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Some codebases will explicitly specify a return type for documentation purposes, to prevent accidental changes, or just for personal preference.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Anonymous functions are a little bit different from function declarations.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] When a function appears in a place where TypeScript can determine how it’s going to be called, the parameters of that function are automatically given types.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Even though the parameter `s` didn’t have a type annotation, TypeScript used the types of the `forEach` function, along with the inferred type of the array, to determine the type `s` will have.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This process is called *contextual typing* because the *context* that the function occurred within informs what type it should have.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Similar to the inference rules, you don’t need to explicitly learn how this happens, but understanding that it *does* happen can help you notice when type annotations aren’t needed.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Later, we’ll see more examples of how the context that a value occurs in can affect its type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Apart from primitives, the most common sort of type you’ll encounter is an *object type*.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This refers to any JavaScript value with properties, which is almost all of them!
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] To define an object type, we simply list its properties and their types.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Here, we annotated the parameter with a type with two properties - `x` and `y` - which are both of type `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can use `,` or `;` to separate the properties, and the last separator is optional either way.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The type part of each property is also optional.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] If you don’t specify a type, it will be assumed to be `any`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Object types can also specify that some or all of their properties are *optional*.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] In JavaScript, if you access a property that doesn’t exist, you’ll get the value `undefined` rather than a runtime error.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Because of this, when you *read* from an optional property, you’ll have to check for `undefined` before using it.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript’s type system allows you to build new types out of existing ones using a large variety of operators.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Now that we know how to write a few types, it’s time to start *combining* them in interesting ways.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The first way to combine types you might see is a *union* type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] A union type is a type formed from two or more other types, representing values that may be *any one* of those types.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] We refer to each of these types as the union’s *members*.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] It’s easy to *provide* a value matching a union type - simply provide a type matching any of the union’s members.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] If you *have* a value of a union type, how do you work with it?
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript will only allow an operation if it is valid for *every* member of the union.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The solution is to *narrow* the union with code, the same as you would in JavaScript without type annotations.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] *Narrowing* occurs when TypeScript can deduce a more specific type for a value based on the structure of the code.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Notice that in the `else` branch, we don’t need to do anything special - if `x` wasn’t a `string[]`, then it must have been a `string`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Sometimes you’ll have a union where all the members have something in common.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] For example, both arrays and strings have a `slice` method.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] We’ve been using object types and union types by writing them directly in type annotations.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This is convenient, but it’s common to want to use the same type more than once and refer to it by a single name.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] A *type alias* is exactly that - a *name* for any *type*.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can actually use a type alias to give a name to any type at all, not just an object type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Note that aliases are *only* aliases - you cannot use type aliases to create different/distinct “versions” of the same type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] When you use the alias, it’s exactly as if you had written the aliased type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Just like when we used a type alias above, the example works just as if we had used an anonymous object type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript is only concerned with the *structure* of the value we passed to `printCoord` - it only cares that it has the expected properties.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Being concerned only with the structure and capabilities of types is why we call TypeScript a *structurally typed* type system.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Type aliases and interfaces are very similar, and in many cases you can choose between them freely.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Almost all features of an `interface` are available in `type`, the key distinction is that a type cannot be re-opened to add new properties vs an interface which is always extendable.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You’ll learn more about these concepts in later chapters, so don’t worry if you don’t understand all of these right away.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] For the most part, you can choose based on personal preference, and TypeScript will tell you if it needs something to be the other kind of declaration.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] If you would like a heuristic, use `interface` until you need to use features from `type`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Sometimes you will have information about the type of a value that TypeScript can’t know about.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] For example, if you’re using `document.getElementById`, TypeScript only knows that this will return *some* kind of `HTMLElement`, but you might know that your page will always have an `HTMLCanvasElement` with a given ID.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Like a type annotation, type assertions are removed by the compiler and won’t affect the runtime behavior of your code.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript only allows type assertions which convert to a *more specific* or *less specific* version of a type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Sometimes this rule can be too conservative and will disallow more complex coercions that might be valid.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] In addition to the general types `string` and `number`, we can refer to *specific* strings and numbers in type positions.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] One way to think about this is to consider how JavaScript comes with different ways to declare a variable.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Both `var` and `let` allow for changing what is held inside the variable, and `const` does not.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This is reflected in how TypeScript creates types for literals.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] It’s not much use to have a variable that can only have one value!
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] There’s one more kind of literal type: boolean literals.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] There are only two boolean literal types, and as you might guess, they are the types `true` and `false`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The type `boolean` itself is actually just an alias for the union `true | false`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] When you initialize a variable with an object, TypeScript assumes that the properties of that object might change values later.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript doesn’t assume the assignment of `1` to a field which previously had `0` is an error.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Another way of saying this is that `obj.counter` must have the type `number`, not `0`, because types are used to determine both *reading* and *writing* behavior.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] In the above example `req.method` is inferred to be `string`, not `"GET"`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Because code can be evaluated between the creation of `req` and the call of `handleRequest` which could assign a new string like `"GUESS"` to `req.method`, TypeScript considers this code to have an error.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The `as const` suffix acts like `const` but for the type system, ensuring that all properties are assigned the literal type instead of a more general version like `string` or `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] JavaScript has two primitive values used to signal absent or uninitialized value: `null` and `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript has two corresponding *types* by the same names.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] How these types behave depends on whether you have the `strictNullChecks` option on.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] With `strictNullChecks` *off*, values that might be `null` or `undefined` can still be accessed normally, and the values `null` and `undefined` can be assigned to a property of any type.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] This is similar to how languages without null checks (e.g.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] The lack of checking for these values tends to be a major source of bugs; we always recommend people turn `strictNullChecks` on if it’s practical to do so in their codebase.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] With `strictNullChecks` *on*, when a value is `null` or `undefined`, you will need to test for those values before using methods or properties on that value.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] TypeScript also has a special syntax for removing `null` and `undefined` from a type without doing any explicit checking.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Just like other type assertions, this doesn’t change the runtime behavior of your code, so it’s important to only use `!` when you know that the value *can’t* be `null` or `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Enums are a feature added to JavaScript by TypeScript which allows for describing a value which could be one of a set of possible named constants.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Unlike most TypeScript features, this is *not* a type-level addition to JavaScript but something added to the language and runtime.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] Because of this, it’s a feature which you should know exists, but maybe hold off on using unless you are sure.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can read more about enums in the Enum reference page.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] It’s worth mentioning the rest of the primitives in JavaScript which are represented in the type system.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can learn more about BigInt in the TypeScript 3.2 release notes.
[src:typescript-docs/everyday-types] You can learn more about them in Symbols reference page.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Functions are the basic building block of any application, whether they’re local functions, imported from another module, or methods on a class.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] They’re also values, and just like other values, TypeScript has many ways to describe how functions can be called.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Let’s learn about how to write types that describe functions.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The simplest way to describe a function is with a *function type expression*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The syntax `(a: string) => void` means “a function with one parameter, named `a`, of type `string`, that doesn’t have a return value”.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Just like with function declarations, if a parameter type isn’t specified, it’s implicitly `any`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In JavaScript, functions can have properties in addition to being callable.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] However, the function type expression syntax doesn’t allow for declaring properties.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Note that the syntax is slightly different compared to a function type expression - use `:` between the parameter list and the return type rather than `=>`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] JavaScript functions can also be invoked with the `new` operator.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] TypeScript refers to these as *constructors* because they usually create a new object.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Some objects, like JavaScript’s `Date` object, can be called with or without `new`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] It’s common to write a function where the types of the input relate to the type of the output, or where the types of two inputs are related in some way.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This function does its job, but unfortunately has the return type `any`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] It’d be better if the function returned the type of the array element.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In TypeScript, *generics* are used when we want to describe a correspondence between two values.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] By adding a type parameter `Type` to this function and using it in two places, we’ve created a link between the input of the function (the array) and the output (the return value).
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Note that we didn’t have to specify `Type` in this sample.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The type was *inferred* - chosen automatically - by TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] We can use multiple type parameters as well.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Note that in this example, TypeScript could infer both the type of the `Input` type parameter (from the given `string` array), as well as the `Output` type parameter based on the return value of the function expression (`number`).
[src:typescript-docs/functions] We’ve written some generic functions that can work on *any* kind of value.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Sometimes we want to relate two values, but can only operate on a certain subset of values.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In this case, we can use a *constraint* to limit the kinds of types that a type parameter can accept.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Let’s write a function that returns the longer of two values.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] To do this, we need a `length` property that’s a number.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] There are a few interesting things to note in this example.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] We allowed TypeScript to *infer* the return type of `longest`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Return type inference also works on generic functions.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Because we constrained `Type` to `{ length: number }`, we were allowed to access the `.length` property of the `a` and `b` parameters.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Without the type constraint, we wouldn’t be able to access those properties because the values might have been some other type without a length property.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The types of `longerArray` and `longerString` were inferred based on the arguments.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Remember, generics are all about relating two or more values with the same type!
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Finally, just as we’d like, the call to `longest(10, 100)` is rejected because the `number` type doesn’t have a `.length` property.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] It might look like this function is OK - `Type` is constrained to `{ length: number }`, and the function either returns `Type` or a value matching that constraint.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The problem is that the function promises to return the *same* kind of object as was passed in, not just *some* object matching the constraint.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] TypeScript can usually infer the intended type arguments in a generic call, but not always.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Writing generic functions is fun, and it can be easy to get carried away with type parameters.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Having too many type parameters or using constraints where they aren’t needed can make inference less successful, frustrating callers of your function.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] These might seem identical at first glance, but `firstElement1` is a much better way to write this function.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Its inferred return type is `Type`, but `firstElement2`’s inferred return type is `any` because TypeScript has to resolve the `arr[0]` expression using the constraint type, rather than “waiting” to resolve the element during a call.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] We’ve created a type parameter `Func` that *doesn’t relate two values*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] That’s always a red flag, because it means callers wanting to specify type arguments have to manually specify an extra type argument for no reason.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] `Func` doesn’t do anything but make the function harder to read and reason about!
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Remember, type parameters are for *relating the types of multiple values*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] If a type parameter is only used once in the function signature, it’s not relating anything.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This includes the inferred return type; for example, if `Str` was part of the inferred return type of `greet`, it would be relating the argument and return types, so would be used *twice* despite appearing only once in the written code.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Functions in JavaScript often take a variable number of arguments.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Although the parameter is specified as type `number`, the `x` parameter will actually have the type `number | undefined` because unspecified parameters in JavaScript get the value `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Now in the body of `f`, `x` will have type `number` because any `undefined` argument will be replaced with `10`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] What this *actually* means is that *`callback` might get invoked with one argument*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In JavaScript, if you call a function with more arguments than there are parameters, the extra arguments are simply ignored.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Functions with fewer parameters (of the same types) can always take the place of functions with more parameters.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Some JavaScript functions can be called in a variety of argument counts and types.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] For example, you might write a function to produce a `Date` that takes either a timestamp (one argument) or a month/day/year specification (three arguments).
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In TypeScript, we can specify a function that can be called in different ways by writing *overload signatures*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In this example, we wrote two overloads: one accepting one argument, and another accepting three arguments.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] These first two signatures are called the *overload signatures*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Then, we wrote a function implementation with a compatible signature.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Functions have an *implementation* signature, but this signature can’t be called directly.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Even though we wrote a function with two optional parameters after the required one, it can’t be called with two parameters!
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Again, the signature used to write the function body can’t be “seen” from the outside.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The implementation signature must also be *compatible* with the overload signatures.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Like generics, there are a few guidelines you should follow when using function overloads.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Following these principles will make your function easier to call, easier to understand, and easier to implement.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This function is fine; we can invoke it with strings or arrays.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Callers can invoke this with either sort of value, and as an added bonus, we don’t have to figure out a correct implementation signature.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] TypeScript understands that the function `user.becomeAdmin` has a corresponding `this` which is the outer object `user`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] `this`, *heh*, can be enough for a lot of cases, but there are a lot of cases where you need more control over what object `this` represents.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The JavaScript specification states that you cannot have a parameter called `this`, and so TypeScript uses that syntax space to let you declare the type for `this` in the function body.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This pattern is common with callback-style APIs, where another object typically controls when your function is called.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] There are some additional types you’ll want to recognize that appear often when working with function types.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Like all types, you can use them everywhere, but these are especially relevant in the context of functions.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] `void` represents the return value of functions which don’t return a value.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In JavaScript, a function that doesn’t return any value will implicitly return the value `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] However, `void` and `undefined` are not the same thing in TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] There are further details at the end of this chapter.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The special type `object` refers to any value that isn’t a primitive (`string`, `number`, `bigint`, `boolean`, `symbol`, `null`, or `undefined`).
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This is different from the *empty object type* `{ }`, and also different from the global type `Object`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] It’s very likely you will never use `Object`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Note that in JavaScript, function values are objects: They have properties, have `Object.prototype` in their prototype chain, are `instanceof Object`, you can call `Object.keys` on them, and so on.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] For this reason, function types are considered to be `object`s in TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The `unknown` type represents *any* value.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This is useful when describing function types because you can describe functions that accept any value without having `any` values in your function body.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The `never` type represents values which are *never* observed.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In a return type, this means that the function throws an exception or terminates execution of the program.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] `never` also appears when TypeScript determines there’s nothing left in a union.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The global type `Function` describes properties like `bind`, `call`, `apply`, and others present on all function values in JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This is an *untyped function call* and is generally best avoided because of the unsafe `any` return type.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] If you need to accept an arbitrary function but don’t intend to call it, the type `() => void` is generally safer.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In addition to using optional parameters or overloads to make functions that can accept a variety of fixed argument counts, we can also define functions that take an *unbounded* number of arguments using *rest parameters*.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] In TypeScript, the type annotation on these parameters is implicitly `any[]` instead of `any`, and any type annotation given must be of the form `Array<T>` or `T[]`, or a tuple type (which we’ll learn about later).
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Conversely, we can *provide* a variable number of arguments from an iterable object (for example, an array) using the spread syntax.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Note that in general, TypeScript does not assume that arrays are immutable.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Using rest arguments may require turning on `downlevelIteration` when targeting older runtimes.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] You can use parameter destructuring to conveniently unpack objects provided as an argument into one or more local variables in the function body.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] The `void` return type for functions can produce some unusual, but expected behavior.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Contextual typing with a return type of `void` does **not** force functions to **not** return something.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] Another way to say this is a contextual function type with a `void` return type (`type voidFunc = () => void`), when implemented, can return *any* other value, but it will be ignored.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] This behavior exists so that the following code is valid even though `Array.prototype.push` returns a number and the `Array.prototype.forEach` method expects a function with a return type of `void`.
[src:typescript-docs/functions] There is one other special case to be aware of, when a literal function definition has a `void` return type, that function must **not** return anything.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] A major part of software engineering is building components that not only have well-defined and consistent APIs, but are also reusable.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Components that are capable of working on the data of today as well as the data of tomorrow will give you the most flexible capabilities for building up large software systems.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] In languages like C# and Java, one of the main tools in the toolbox for creating reusable components is *generics*, that is, being able to create a component that can work over a variety of types rather than a single one.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This allows users to consume these components and use their own types.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] To start off, let’s do the “hello world” of generics: the identity function.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] The identity function is a function that will return back whatever is passed in.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] You can think of this in a similar way to the `echo` command.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] While using `any` is certainly generic in that it will cause the function to accept any and all types for the type of `arg`, we actually are losing the information about what that type was when the function returns.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] If we passed in a number, the only information we have is that any type could be returned.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Instead, we need a way of capturing the type of the argument in such a way that we can also use it to denote what is being returned.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Here, we will use a *type variable*, a special kind of variable that works on types rather than values.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] We’ve now added a type variable `Type` to the identity function.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This `Type` allows us to capture the type the user provides (e.g.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] `number`), so that we can use that information later.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Here, we use `Type` again as the return type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] On inspection, we can now see the same type is used for the argument and the return type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This allows us to traffic that type information in one side of the function and out the other.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] We say that this version of the `identity` function is generic, as it works over a range of types.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Unlike using `any`, it’s also just as precise (i.e., it doesn’t lose any information) as the first `identity` function that used numbers for the argument and return type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Once we’ve written the generic identity function, we can call it in one of two ways.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Here we explicitly set `Type` to be `string` as one of the arguments to the function call, denoted using the `<>` around the arguments rather than `()`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] The second way is also perhaps the most common.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Notice that we didn’t have to explicitly pass the type in the angle brackets (`<>`); the compiler just looked at the value `"myString"`, and set `Type` to its type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] While type argument inference can be a helpful tool to keep code shorter and more readable, you may need to explicitly pass in the type arguments as we did in the previous example when the compiler fails to infer the type, as may happen in more complex examples.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] When you begin to use generics, you’ll notice that when you create generic functions like `identity`, the compiler will enforce that you use any generically typed parameters in the body of the function correctly.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] That is, that you actually treat these parameters as if they could be any and all types.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] What if we want to also log the length of the argument `arg` to the console with each call?
