[src:typescript-docs/generics] Covariance and contravariance are type theory terms that describe what the relationship between two generic types is.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] We can use a `Producer<Cat>` where a `Producer<Animal>` is expected, because a `Cat` is an `Animal`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This relationship is called *covariance*: the relationship from `Producer<T>` to `Producer<U>` is the same as the relationship from `T` to `U`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Then we can use a `Consumer<Animal>` where a `Consumer<Cat>` is expected, because any function that is capable of accepting an `Animal` must also be capable of accepting a `Cat`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This relationship is called *contravariance*: the relationship from `Consumer<T>` to `Consumer<U>` is the same as the relationship from `U` to `T`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Note the reversal of direction as compared to covariance!
[src:typescript-docs/generics] This is why contravariance “cancels itself out” but covariance doesn’t.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] In a structural type system like TypeScript’s, covariance and contravariance are naturally emergent behaviors that follow from the definition of types.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] TypeScript has a structural type system, so when comparing two types, e.g. to see if a `Producer<Cat>` can be used where a `Producer<Animal>` is expected, the usual algorithm would be structurally expand both of those definitions, and compare their structures.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] However, variance allows for an extremely useful optimization: if `Producer<T>` is covariant on `T`, then we can simply check `Cat` and `Animal` instead, as we know they’ll have the same relationship as `Producer<Cat>` and `Producer<Animal>`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Note that this logic can only be used when we’re examining two instantiations of the same type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] If we have a `Producer<T>` and a `FastProducer<U>`, there’s no guarantee that `T` and `U` necessarily refer to the same positions in these types, so this check will always be performed structurally.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Because variance is a naturally emergent property of structural types, TypeScript automatically *infers* the variance of every generic type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] **In extremely rare cases** involving certain kinds of circular types, this measurement can be inaccurate.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Only do this if you are writing the same variance that *should* occur structurally.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] It’s critical to reinforce that variance annotations are only in effect during an instantiation-based comparison.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] They have no effect during a structural comparison.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Here, the object literal’s `make` function returns `number`, which we might expect to cause an error because `number` isn’t `string | number`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] However, this isn’t an instantiation-based comparison, because the object literal is an anonymous type, not a `Producer<string | number>`.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] It’s very important to only write variance annotations if you absolutely know why you’re doing it, what their limitations are, and when they aren’t in effect.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Whether TypeScript uses an instantiation-based comparison or structural comparison is not a specified behavior and may change from version to version for correctness or performance reasons, so you should only ever write variance annotations when they match the structural behavior of a type.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Don’t use variance annotations to try to “force” a particular variance; this will cause unpredictable behavior in your code.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Remember, TypeScript can automatically infer variance from your generic types.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] It’s almost never necessary to write a variance annotation, and you should only do so when you’ve identified a specific need.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Variance annotations *do not* change the structural behavior of a type, and depending on the situation, you might see a structural comparison made when you expected an instantiation-based comparison.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Variance annotations can’t be used to modify how types behave in these structural contexts, and shouldn’t be written unless the annotation is the same as the structural definition.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Because this is difficult to get right, and TypeScript can correctly infer variance in the vast majority of cases, you should not find yourself writing variance annotations in normal code.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] You *may* find temporary variance annotations useful in a “type debugging” situation, because variance annotations are checked.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] However, variance annotations are allowed to be stricter (e.g.
[src:typescript-docs/generics] `in out` is valid if the actual variance is covariant).
[src:typescript-docs/generics] Be sure to remove your variance annotations once you’re done debugging.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Imagine we have a function called `padLeft`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If `padding` is a `number`, it will treat that as the number of spaces we want to prepend to `input`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If `padding` is a `string`, it should just prepend `padding` to `input`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Let’s try to implement the logic for when `padLeft` is passed a `number` for `padding`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Uh-oh, we’re getting an error on `padding`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript is warning us that we’re passing a value with type `number | string` to the `repeat` function, which only accepts a `number`, and it’s right.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In other words, we haven’t explicitly checked if `padding` is a `number` first, nor are we handling the case where it’s a `string`, so let’s do exactly that.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If this mostly looks like uninteresting JavaScript code, that’s sort of the point.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Apart from the annotations we put in place, this TypeScript code looks like JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The idea is that TypeScript’s type system aims to make it as easy as possible to write typical JavaScript code without bending over backwards to get type safety.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] While it might not look like much, there’s actually a lot going on under the covers here.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Much like how TypeScript analyzes runtime values using static types, it overlays type analysis on JavaScript’s runtime control flow constructs like `if/else`, conditional ternaries, loops, truthiness checks, etc., which can all affect those types.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Within our `if` check, TypeScript sees `typeof padding === "number"` and understands that as a special form of code called a *type guard*.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript follows possible paths of execution that our programs can take to analyze the most specific possible type of a value at a given position.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] It looks at these special checks (called *type guards*) and assignments, and the process of refining types to more specific types than declared is called *narrowing*.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In many editors we can observe these types as they change, and we’ll even do so in our examples.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] There are a couple of different constructs TypeScript understands for narrowing.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As we’ve seen, JavaScript supports a `typeof` operator which can give very basic information about the type of values we have at runtime.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Like we saw with `padLeft`, this operator comes up pretty often in a number of JavaScript libraries, and TypeScript can understand it to narrow types in different branches.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In TypeScript, checking against the value returned by `typeof` is a type guard.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Because TypeScript encodes how `typeof` operates on different values, it knows about some of its quirks in JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] For example, notice that in the list above, `typeof` doesn’t return the string `null`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In the `printAll` function, we try to check if `strs` is an object to see if it’s an array type (now might be a good time to reinforce that arrays are object types in JavaScript).
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] But it turns out that in JavaScript, `typeof null` is actually `"object"`!
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] This is one of those unfortunate accidents of history.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Users with enough experience might not be surprised, but not everyone has run into this in JavaScript; luckily, TypeScript lets us know that `strs` was only narrowed down to `string[] | null` instead of just `string[]`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] This might be a good segue into what we’ll call “truthiness” checking.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Truthiness might not be a word you’ll find in the dictionary, but it’s very much something you’ll hear about in JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In JavaScript, we can use any expression in conditionals, `&&`s, `||`s, `if` statements, Boolean negations (`!`), and more.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As an example, `if` statements don’t expect their condition to always have the type `boolean`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In JavaScript, constructs like `if` first “coerce” their conditions to `boolean`s to make sense of them, and then choose their branches depending on whether the result is `true` or `false`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] all coerce to `false`, and other values get coerced to `true`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] You can always coerce values to `boolean`s by running them through the `Boolean` function, or by using the shorter double-Boolean negation.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] It’s fairly popular to leverage this behavior, especially for guarding against values like `null` or `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As an example, let’s try using it for our `printAll` function.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] You’ll notice that we’ve gotten rid of the error above by checking if `strs` is truthy.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Keep in mind though that truthiness checking on primitives can often be error prone.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We wrapped the entire body of the function in a truthy check, but this has a subtle downside: we may no longer be handling the empty string case correctly.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript doesn’t hurt us here at all, but this behavior is worth noting if you’re less familiar with JavaScript.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript can often help you catch bugs early on, but if you choose to do *nothing* with a value, there’s only so much that it can do without being overly prescriptive.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If you want, you can make sure you handle situations like these with a linter.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] One last word on narrowing by truthiness is that Boolean negations with `!` filter out from negated branches.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript also uses `switch` statements and equality checks like `===`, `!==`, `==`, and `!=` to narrow types.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] When we checked that `x` and `y` are both equal in the above example, TypeScript knew their types also had to be equal.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Since `string` is the only common type that both `x` and `y` could take on, TypeScript knows that `x` and `y` must be `string`s in the first branch.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Checking against specific literal values (as opposed to variables) works also.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In our section about truthiness narrowing, we wrote a `printAll` function which was error-prone because it accidentally didn’t handle empty strings properly.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Instead we could have done a specific check to block out `null`s, and TypeScript still correctly removes `null` from the type of `strs`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] JavaScript’s looser equality checks with `==` and `!=` also get narrowed correctly.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If you’re unfamiliar, checking whether something `== null` actually not only checks whether it is specifically the value `null` - it also checks whether it’s potentially `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The same applies to `== undefined`: it checks whether a value is either `null` or `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] JavaScript has an operator for determining if an object or its prototype chain has a property with a name: the `in` operator.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript takes this into account as a way to narrow down potential types.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] For example, with the code: `"value" in x` where `"value"` is a string literal and `x` is a union type.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The “true” branch narrows `x`’s types which have either an optional or required property `value`, and the “false” branch narrows to types which have an optional or missing property `value`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] To reiterate, optional properties will exist in both sides for narrowing.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] JavaScript has an operator for checking whether or not a value is an “instance” of another value.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] More specifically, in JavaScript `x instanceof Foo` checks whether the *prototype chain* of `x` contains `Foo.prototype`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] While we won’t dive deep here, and you’ll see more of this when we get into classes, they can still be useful for most values that can be constructed with `new`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As you might have guessed, `instanceof` is also a type guard, and TypeScript narrows in branches guarded by `instanceof`s.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As we mentioned earlier, when we assign to any variable, TypeScript looks at the right side of the assignment and narrows the left side appropriately.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Notice that each of these assignments is valid.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Even though the observed type of `x` changed to `number` after our first assignment, we were still able to assign a `string` to `x`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] This is because the *declared type* of `x` - the type that `x` started with - is `string | number`, and assignability is always checked against the declared type.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] If we’d assigned a `boolean` to `x`, we’d have seen an error since that wasn’t part of the declared type.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Up until this point, we’ve gone through some basic examples of how TypeScript narrows within specific branches.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] But there’s a bit more going on than just walking up from every variable and looking for type guards in `if`s, `while`s, conditionals, etc.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] `padLeft` returns from within its first `if` block.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] TypeScript was able to analyze this code and see that the rest of the body (`return padding + input;`) is *unreachable* in the case where `padding` is a `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] As a result, it was able to remove `number` from the type of `padding` (narrowing from `string | number` to `string`) for the rest of the function.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] This analysis of code based on reachability is called *control flow analysis*, and TypeScript uses this flow analysis to narrow types as it encounters type guards and assignments.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] When a variable is analyzed, control flow can split off and re-merge over and over again, and that variable can be observed to have a different type at each point.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We’ve worked with existing JavaScript constructs to handle narrowing so far, however sometimes you want more direct control over how types change throughout your code.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] `pet is Fish` is our type predicate in this example.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] A predicate takes the form `parameterName is Type`, where `parameterName` must be the name of a parameter from the current function signature.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Any time `isFish` is called with some variable, TypeScript will *narrow* that variable to that specific type if the original type is compatible.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Notice that TypeScript not only knows that `pet` is a `Fish` in the `if` branch; it also knows that in the `else` branch, you *don’t* have a `Fish`, so you must have a `Bird`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In addition, classes can use `this is Type` to narrow their type.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Types can also be narrowed using Assertion functions.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Most of the examples we’ve looked at so far have focused around narrowing single variables with simple types like `string`, `boolean`, and `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] While this is common, most of the time in JavaScript we’ll be dealing with slightly more complex structures.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] For some motivation, let’s imagine we’re trying to encode shapes like circles and squares.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Circles keep track of their radiuses and squares keep track of their side lengths.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We’ll use a field called `kind` to tell which shape we’re dealing with.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Here’s a first attempt at defining `Shape`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Notice we’re using a union of string literal types: `"circle"` and `"square"` to tell us whether we should treat the shape as a circle or square respectively.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] By using `"circle" | "square"` instead of `string`, we can avoid misspelling issues.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We can write a `getArea` function that applies the right logic based on if it’s dealing with a circle or square.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Under `strictNullChecks` that gives us an error - which is appropriate since `radius` might not be defined.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] But what if we perform the appropriate checks on the `kind` property?
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Hmm, TypeScript still doesn’t know what to do here.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We’ve hit a point where we know more about our values than the type checker does.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We could try to use a non-null assertion (a `!` after `shape.radius`) to say that `radius` is definitely present.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We had to shout a bit at the type-checker with those non-null assertions (`!`) to convince it that `shape.radius` was defined, but those assertions are error-prone if we start to move code around.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Additionally, outside of `strictNullChecks` we’re able to accidentally access any of those fields anyway (since optional properties are just assumed to always be present when reading them).
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The problem with this encoding of `Shape` is that the type-checker doesn’t have any way to know whether or not `radius` or `sideLength` are present based on the `kind` property.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] We need to communicate what *we* know to the type checker.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] With that in mind, let’s take another swing at defining `Shape`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Here, we’ve properly separated `Shape` out into two types with different values for the `kind` property, but `radius` and `sideLength` are declared as required properties in their respective types.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Let’s see what happens here when we try to access the `radius` of a `Shape`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Like with our first definition of `Shape`, this is still an error.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] When `radius` was optional, we got an error (with `strictNullChecks` enabled) because TypeScript couldn’t tell whether the property was present.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Now that `Shape` is a union, TypeScript is telling us that `shape` might be a `Square`, and `Square`s don’t have `radius` defined on them!
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Both interpretations are correct, but only the union encoding of `Shape` will cause an error regardless of how `strictNullChecks` is configured.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] But what if we tried checking the `kind` property again?
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] When every type in a union contains a common property with literal types, TypeScript considers that to be a *discriminated union*, and can narrow out the members of the union.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In this case, `kind` was that common property (which is what’s considered a *discriminant* property of `Shape`).
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Checking whether the `kind` property was `"circle"` got rid of every type in `Shape` that didn’t have a `kind` property with the type `"circle"`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] That narrowed `shape` down to the type `Circle`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The same checking works with `switch` statements as well.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Now we can try to write our complete `getArea` without any pesky `!` non-null assertions.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The important thing here was the encoding of `Shape`.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Communicating the right information to TypeScript - that `Circle` and `Square` were really two separate types with specific `kind` fields - was crucial.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Doing that lets us write type-safe TypeScript code that looks no different than the JavaScript we would’ve written otherwise.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] From there, the type system was able to do the “right” thing and figure out the types in each branch of our `switch` statement.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] Discriminated unions are useful for more than just talking about circles and squares.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] They’re good for representing any sort of messaging scheme in JavaScript, like when sending messages over the network (client/server communication), or encoding mutations in a state management framework.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] When narrowing, you can reduce the options of a union to a point where you have removed all possibilities and have nothing left.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] In those cases, TypeScript will use a `never` type to represent a state which shouldn’t exist.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] The `never` type is assignable to every type; however, no type is assignable to `never` (except `never` itself).
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] This means you can use narrowing and rely on `never` turning up to do exhaustive checking in a `switch` statement.
[src:typescript-docs/narrowing] For example, adding a `default` to our `getArea` function which tries to assign the shape to `never` will not raise an error when every possible case has been handled.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In JavaScript, the fundamental way that we group and pass around data is through objects.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In TypeScript, we represent those through *object types*.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In all three examples above, we’ve written functions that take objects that contain the property `name` (which must be a `string`) and `age` (which must be a `number`).
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We have cheat-sheets available for both `type` and `interface`, if you want a quick look at the important every-day syntax at a glance.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Each property in an object type can specify a couple of things: the type, whether the property is optional, and whether the property can be written to.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Much of the time, we’ll find ourselves dealing with objects that *might* have a property set.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In those cases, we can mark those properties as *optional* by adding a question mark (`?`) to the end of their names.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In this example, both `xPos` and `yPos` are considered optional.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We can choose to provide either of them, so every call above to `paintShape` is valid.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] All optionality really says is that if the property *is* set, it better have a specific type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We can also read from those properties - but when we do under `strictNullChecks`, TypeScript will tell us they’re potentially `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In JavaScript, even if the property has never been set, we can still access it - it’s just going to give us the value `undefined`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We can just handle `undefined` specially by checking for it.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Note that this pattern of setting defaults for unspecified values is so common that JavaScript has syntax to support it.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Here we used a destructuring pattern for `paintShape`’s parameter, and provided default values for `xPos` and `yPos`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Now `xPos` and `yPos` are both definitely present within the body of `paintShape`, but optional for any callers to `paintShape`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Properties can also be marked as `readonly` for TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] While it won’t change any behavior at runtime, a property marked as `readonly` can’t be written to during type-checking.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Using the `readonly` modifier doesn’t necessarily imply that a value is totally immutable - or in other words, that its internal contents can’t be changed.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It just means the property itself can’t be re-written to.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It’s important to manage expectations of what `readonly` implies.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It’s useful to signal intent during development time for TypeScript on how an object should be used.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] TypeScript doesn’t factor in whether properties on two types are `readonly` when checking whether those types are compatible, so `readonly` properties can also change via aliasing.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Using mapping modifiers, you can remove `readonly` attributes.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Sometimes you don’t know all the names of a type’s properties ahead of time, but you do know the shape of the values.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Above, we have a `StringArray` interface which has an index signature.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This index signature states that when a `StringArray` is indexed with a `number`, it will return a `string`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Only some types are allowed for index signature properties: `string`, `number`, `symbol`, template string patterns, and union types consisting only of these.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It is possible to support multiple types of indexers...
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It is possible to support multiple types of indexers.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Note that when using both `number` and `string` indexers, the type returned from a numeric indexer must be a subtype of the type returned from the string indexer.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This is because when indexing with a `number`, JavaScript will actually convert that to a `string` before indexing into an object.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] That means that indexing with `100` (a `number`) is the same thing as indexing with `"100"` (a `string`), so the two need to be consistent.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] While string index signatures are a powerful way to describe the “dictionary” pattern, they also enforce that all properties match their return type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This is because a string index declares that `obj.property` is also available as `obj["property"]`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] You can’t set `myArray[2]` because the index signature is `readonly`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Where and how an object is assigned a type can make a difference in the type system.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] One of the key examples of this is in excess property checking, which validates the object more thoroughly when it is created and assigned to an object type during creation.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Notice the given argument to `createSquare` is spelled *`colour`* instead of `color`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In plain JavaScript, this sort of thing fails silently.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] You could argue that this program is correctly typed, since the `width` properties are compatible, there’s no `color` property present, and the extra `colour` property is insignificant.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] However, TypeScript takes the stance that there’s probably a bug in this code.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Object literals get special treatment and undergo *excess property checking* when assigning them to other variables, or passing them as arguments.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Getting around these checks is actually really simple.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] However, a better approach might be to add a string index signature if you’re sure that the object can have some extra properties that are used in some special way.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Here we’re saying that `SquareConfig` can have any number of properties, and as long as they aren’t `color` or `width`, their types don’t matter.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] The above workaround will work as long as you have a common property between `squareOptions` and `SquareConfig`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In this example, it was the property `width`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It will however, fail if the variable does not have any common object property.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Keep in mind that for simple code like above, you probably shouldn’t be trying to “get around” these checks.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] For more complex object literals that have methods and hold state, you might need to keep these techniques in mind, but a majority of excess property errors are actually bugs.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] That means if you’re running into excess property checking problems for something like option bags, you might need to revise some of your type declarations.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In this instance, if it’s okay to pass an object with both a `color` or `colour` property to `createSquare`, you should fix up the definition of `SquareConfig` to reflect that.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It’s pretty common to have types that might be more specific versions of other types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] For example, we might have a `BasicAddress` type that describes the fields necessary for sending letters and packages in the U.S.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In some situations that’s enough, but addresses often have a unit number associated with them if the building at an address has multiple units.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We can then describe an `AddressWithUnit`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This does the job, but the downside here is that we had to repeat all the other fields from `BasicAddress` when our changes were purely additive.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Instead, we can extend the original `BasicAddress` type and just add the new fields that are unique to `AddressWithUnit`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] The `extends` keyword on an `interface` allows us to effectively copy members from other named types, and add whatever new members we want.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This can be useful for cutting down the amount of type declaration boilerplate we have to write, and for signaling intent that several different declarations of the same property might be related.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] For example, `AddressWithUnit` didn’t need to repeat the `street` property, and because `street` originates from `BasicAddress`, a reader will know that those two types are related in some way.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] `interface`s can also extend from multiple types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] `interface`s allowed us to build up new types from other types by extending them.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] TypeScript provides another construct called *intersection types* that is mainly used to combine existing object types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] An intersection type is defined using the `&` operator.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Here, we’ve intersected `Colorful` and `Circle` to produce a new type that has all the members of `Colorful` *and* `Circle`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We just looked at two ways to combine types which are similar, but are actually subtly different.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] With interfaces, we could use an `extends` clause to extend from other types, and we were able to do something similar with intersections and name the result with a type alias.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] The principal difference between the two is how conflicts are handled, and that difference is typically one of the main reasons why you’d pick one over the other between an interface and a type alias of an intersection type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] If interfaces are defined with the same name, TypeScript will attempt to merge them if the properties are compatible.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] If the properties are not compatible (i.e., they have the same property name but different types), TypeScript will raise an error.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In the case of intersection types, properties with different types will be merged automatically.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] When the type is used later, TypeScript will expect the property to satisfy both types simultaneously, which may produce unexpected results.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In this case, Staff would require the name property to be both a string and a number, which results in property being of type `never`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Let’s imagine a `Box` type that can contain any value - `string`s, `number`s, `Giraffe`s, whatever.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Right now, the `contents` property is typed as `any`, which works, but can lead to accidents down the line.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We could instead use `unknown`, but that would mean that in cases where we already know the type of `contents`, we’d need to do precautionary checks, or use error-prone type assertions.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] One type safe approach would be to instead scaffold out different `Box` types for every type of `contents`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] But that means we’ll have to create different functions, or overloads of functions, to operate on these types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Moreover, we might later need to introduce new types and overloads.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This is frustrating, since our box types and overloads are all effectively the same.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Instead, we can make a *generic* `Box` type which declares a *type parameter*.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] You might read this as “A `Box` of `Type` is something whose `contents` have type `Type`”.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Later on, when we refer to `Box`, we have to give a *type argument* in place of `Type`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Think of `Box` as a template for a real type, where `Type` is a placeholder that will get replaced with some other type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] When TypeScript sees `Box<string>`, it will replace every instance of `Type` in `Box<Type>` with `string`, and end up working with something like `{ contents: string }`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] In other words, `Box<string>` and our earlier `StringBox` work identically.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] `Box` is reusable in that `Type` can be substituted with anything.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] That means that when we need a box for a new type, we don’t need to declare a new `Box` type at all (though we certainly could if we wanted to).
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This also means that we can avoid overloads entirely by instead using generic functions.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It is worth noting that type aliases can also be generic.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Since type aliases, unlike interfaces, can describe more than just object types, we can also use them to write other kinds of generic helper types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We’ll circle back to type aliases in just a little bit.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Generic object types are often some sort of container type that work independently of the type of elements they contain.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It’s ideal for data structures to work this way so that they’re re-usable across different data types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] It turns out we’ve been working with a type just like that throughout this handbook: the `Array` type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Whenever we write out types like `number[]` or `string[]`, that’s really just a shorthand for `Array<number>` and `Array<string>`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Much like the `Box` type above, `Array` itself is a generic type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Modern JavaScript also provides other data structures which are generic, like `Map<K, V>`, `Set<T>`, and `Promise<T>`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] All this really means is that because of how `Map`, `Set`, and `Promise` behave, they can work with any sets of types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] The `ReadonlyArray` is a special type that describes arrays that shouldn’t be changed.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Much like the `readonly` modifier for properties, it’s mainly a tool we can use for intent.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] When we see a function that returns `ReadonlyArray`s, it tells us we’re not meant to change the contents at all, and when we see a function that consumes `ReadonlyArray`s, it tells us that we can pass any array into that function without worrying that it will change its contents.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Unlike `Array`, there isn’t a `ReadonlyArray` constructor that we can use.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Instead, we can assign regular `Array`s to `ReadonlyArray`s.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Just as TypeScript provides a shorthand syntax for `Array<Type>` with `Type[]`, it also provides a shorthand syntax for `ReadonlyArray<Type>` with `readonly Type[]`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] One last thing to note is that unlike the `readonly` property modifier, assignability isn’t bidirectional between regular `Array`s and `ReadonlyArray`s.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] A *tuple type* is another sort of `Array` type that knows exactly how many elements it contains, and exactly which types it contains at specific positions.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Here, `StringNumberPair` is a tuple type of `string` and `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Like `ReadonlyArray`, it has no representation at runtime, but is significant to TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] To the type system, `StringNumberPair` describes arrays whose `0` index contains a `string` and whose `1` index contains a `number`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] If we try to index past the number of elements, we’ll get an error.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] We can also destructure tuples using JavaScript’s array destructuring.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Other than those length checks, simple tuple types like these are equivalent to types which are versions of `Array`s that declare properties for specific indexes, and that declare `length` with a numeric literal type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Another thing you may be interested in is that tuples can have optional properties by writing out a question mark (`?` after an element’s type).
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Optional tuple elements can only come at the end, and also affect the type of `length`.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Tuples can also have rest elements, which have to be an array/tuple type.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] A tuple with a rest element has no set “length” - it only has a set of well-known elements in different positions.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Why might optional and rest elements be useful?
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Well, it allows TypeScript to correspond tuples with parameter lists.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This is handy when you want to take a variable number of arguments with a rest parameter, and you need a minimum number of elements, but you don’t want to introduce intermediate variables.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] One final note about tuple types - tuple types have `readonly` variants, and can be specified by sticking a `readonly` modifier in front of them - just like with array shorthand syntax.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] As you might expect, writing to any property of a `readonly` tuple isn’t allowed in TypeScript.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Tuples tend to be created and left un-modified in most code, so annotating types as `readonly` tuples when possible is a good default.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] This is also important given that array literals with `const` assertions will be inferred with `readonly` tuple types.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Here, `distanceFromOrigin` never modifies its elements, but expects a mutable tuple.
[src:typescript-docs/objects] Since `point`’s type was inferred as `readonly [3, 4]`, it won’t be compatible with `[number, number]` since that type can’t guarantee `point`’s elements won’t be mutated.
